🧾 Question: Java – Braces

Implement a Parser class that checks whether a string of brackets is balanced.

A string containing only {, }, (, ) is considered balanced if:

It is an empty string
If a and b are balanced, then ab is balanced
If a is balanced, then (a) and {a} are balanced
🔹 Output Requirement:

Return:

"true" → if string is balanced
"false" → otherwise
📌 Example 1

Input:

{}()
({()})

Output:

true
true
📌 Example 2

Input:

{}(
({)}
(

Output:

false
false
false
💡 Approach (Concept)

Use a Stack:

Push opening brackets ( {
On closing brackets:
Check if stack is empty → false
Pop and match
At the end:
Stack empty → true
Else → false






























Answer:
import java.util.*;
import java.util.Scanner;

// DO NOT use public for Parser
class Parser {
    static String isBalanced(String s) {
        Stack<Character> stack = new Stack<>();

        for (char ch : s.toCharArray()) {

            // Opening brackets
            if (ch == '(' || ch == '{') {
                stack.push(ch);
            }

            // Closing brackets
            else if (ch == ')' || ch == '}') {

                if (stack.isEmpty()) {
                    return "false";
                }

                char top = stack.pop();

                // Check matching
                if ((ch == ')' && top != '(') ||
                    (ch == '}' && top != '{')) {
                    return "false";
                }
            }
        }

        // Final check
        return stack.isEmpty() ? "true" : "false";
    }
}

class Solution {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Parser parser = new Parser();
        Scanner in = new Scanner(System.in);

        while (in.hasNext()) {
            System.out.println(parser.isBalanced(in.next()));
        }

        in.close();
    }
}
